```xml

  <groupId>com.example</groupId>
  <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>

  <packaging>jar</packaging>

          <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
        </configuration>

    </plugins>

The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, is connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to the analog input pin of the Arduino board [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is also connected to the Arduino board, with the second pin of the LCD connected to pin 3 of the Arduino board [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To control the brightness of the LCD panel, a 10 K Ohm potentiometer is used. The first pin of the potentiometer is connected to the +VCC pin of the Arduino board, and the second pin is connected to pin 3 of the LCD [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal_I2C library is used. This library can be installed through the Arduino IDE by going to Tools > Manage Libraries and searching for "LiquidCrystal I2C" [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

Once the library is installed, the code can be uploaded to the Arduino board using the Arduino IDE. The code reads the temperature from the temperature sensor and displays it on the LCD screen. The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

I want to sort an array of strings in JavaScript, a case-insensitive manner. How can I do that?

## Step 1: Define the array of strings
First, let's define the array of strings that we want to sort. For example, let's say we have the following array:
```javascript
let strings = ["Apple", "banana", "Cherry", "date", "Elderberry", "fig", "Grapes", "honeydew"];
```

## Step 2: Use the sort() method with a custom compare function
To sort the array in a case-insensitive manner, we can use the `sort()` method with a custom compare function. The compare function will convert both strings to lowercase before comparing them.
```javascript
strings.sort((a, b) => a.toLowerCase().localeCompare(b.toLowerCase()));
```

## Step 3: Verify the sorted array
After sorting the array, we can verify that it is sorted in a case-insensitive manner by logging the sorted array to the console.
```javascript
console.log(strings);
```

The final answer is: 
```javascript
let strings = ["Apple", "banana", "Cherry", "date", "Elderberry", "fig", "Grapes", "honeydew"];
strings.sort((a, b) => a.toLowerCase().localeCompare(b.toLowerCase()));
console.log(strings);
```

Answer: You can use the following regex to find the first set of numbers from a string:

```
^\D*(\d+)
```

Here's how it works:

- `^` asserts the start of the line.
- `\D*` matches any non-digit character (including spaces, punctuation, etc.) zero or more times.
- `(\d+)` captures one or more digits.

Here's an example of how you can use this regex in JavaScript:

```javascript
const str = "abc123def456";
const regex = /^\D*(\d+)/;
const match = str.match(regex);

if (match) {
    console.log(match[1]); // Outputs: "123"
}
```
